<h1>@HI{{toka}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @N{{}} <strong>@HI{{toka}}</strong>
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@HI{{toka}} is used to list example nouns in the same way that @HI{{ya}} is used. However, @HI{{toka}}
is more informal. Furthermore, @HI{{toka}} can sometimes follow the last noun listed, which @HI{{ya}}
never can.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      A: @HI{{donnna @KT{{supo-tsu}}wo shite imasuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      B: @HI{{sou desune. @KT{{tenisu}}<strong>@HI{{toka}}</strong> @KJ{{water^swim}}<strong>@HI{{toka}}</strong>...}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      A: What kind of sports do you do?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      B: Well ... playing tennis, swimming and so on.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<ol>

